Use a custom `Window` subclass to hook `OnStopped`, `OnResumed`, and `OnDestroying`. Save the draft with `Preferences` (fast and synchronous):

**App.xaml.cs**
```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new MainPage());
}
```

**AppWindow.cs**
```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        SaveDraft(); // Android back-button can skip Stopped
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Page is MainPage mp)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", mp.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Page is MainPage mp)
            mp.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnStopped`** fires when the app is fully backgrounded — save here.
- **`OnResumed`** fires when returning from background — restore here.
- **`OnDestroying`** also saves because on Android the back button can skip `Stopped` entirely.
- **`Resumed` doesn't fire on first launch** (sequence is `Created` → `Activated`), so load initial drafts in your page's constructor or `OnAppearing`.
- Keep handlers fast (<1–2s) to avoid ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS. `Preferences` is ideal for small strings like draft text.
